Lab 7: The Un-deletable File (Immutability)
Title: Protecting the Core Configuration
Difficulty Level: Intermediate → Advanced
Objective: Use filesystem attributes to completely lock down a file, preventing even the root user from deleting or modifying it.

Environment Setup Commands:

cd ~/labs/security
cat << 'EOF' > nginx_core.conf
server {
    listen 80;
    server_name localhost;
}
EOF


Tasks to Perform:

Change the file attributes to make nginx_core.conf immutable using the chattr command.

Switch to the root user (or use sudo) and try to delete the file (sudo rm -f nginx_core.conf). It should fail.

Try to append text to the file (echo "test" | sudo tee -a nginx_core.conf). It should fail.

View the file's special attributes to confirm its status using lsattr.

Remove the immutable flag so the file can be managed normally again.

Expected Outcome: You learn how to lock files at the filesystem level, overriding all standard rwx permissions.
Validation Steps:

lsattr nginx_core.conf should show ----i---------e---- nginx_core.conf.
Common Mistakes: Forgetting that chattr exists and assuming a compromised root account can immediately delete everything.
Real-World Relevance: Hackers and malware often try to alter /etc/passwd or SSH keys. SREs use chattr +i on critical system files so that even if an attacker gains root, they hit a confusing brick wall when trying to modify or delete them.




